\doTocEntry\toclof{}{\csname a:TocLink\endcsname{1}{x1-38006}{}{\numberline {8.2}{\ignorespaces Error propagation of two linear functions, $g_1$ (black line) and $g_2$ (grey line). The input data $\{x_i\}$ are normally distributed around some average value $\bar {x}$. Error propagation estimates the dispersion of the inferred quantity $z_i$ from the dispersion of the measurements $x_i$. Deviations $(x_i-\bar {x})$ from the average $x$-value are reduced (for function $g_1$) or magnified (for function $g_2$) depending on the slope of the functions, resulting in deviations of the dependent variable that are smaller $(z_{i1}-\bar {z}_1)$ or greater $(z_{i2}-\bar {z}_i)$ than $(x_i-\bar {x})$. \relax }}}{91}\relax 
